HREF- Hypertext Reference

Navigation and linking
-When we want to create a link we use the A element, which stands for anchor.
-The "S" in HTTPS stands for secure.
**********************************************************************************************************************************************************************
Images - <img src="image.jpg"alt="brown dog"width="400"height="300">

-There are 4 attributes that need to be included for every image.
1. (SRC), Source attribute which tells the browser which image file to load.
2.(ALT), which provides a text description of the image.
3.Width and Height attribute which determines the size of the image.
4.

The height and width can be specified in the beginning or end. In HTML the order of attributes within an element can be whatever you prefer.
Remember those annoying instances when you are reading an article online and the page keeps shifting around as the images load, disrupting your reading experience?
Well, including the width and height attributes on your images solves that issue. 
**********************************************************************************************************************************************************************
There are 4 main file formats commanly used on the web:
1.GIF
-Simple Animations
-supports 256 colors
-Transparency but not alpha transparency
2.SVG
Scalable Vector Graphics
-not resolution dependant
-used for shapes, text, sketches, logos 
3.PNG
-Alpha Transparency
4.JPG
-Compression
-Flexable format

Responsive Images
-CSS offers a solution for displaying images in different sizes to accommodate both large 
screens and small screens.
